The drug for sixty crowns a day can reduce the risk of a heart attack
Thousands of patients at risk of a heart attack will be able to take the drug, which in terms of cost about sixty crowns (two pounds). Authorities recommend that it be administered to more patients over a longer period of time.
The anti-clotting medicine Ticagrelor reduces the risk of a heart attack in people with heart disease.
The drug is now administered for 12 months after a heart attack to reduce the risk of a stroke or other attack.
The NHS watchdog NICE recommends that the drug be given to people for four years to further reduce the risk of cardiovascular problems.
Now, however, the NHS watchdog NICE recommends that it be given to people for four years to further reduce the risk of cardiovascular problems.
In England, about 140,000 people suffer a heart attack every year, and a quarter of them will have another heart attack or stroke.
Heart attack and stroke are caused by the accumulation of fat, which forms a continuous layer on the walls of the arteries.
If this layer breaks off, a blood clot can form, block blood from entering the heart, and cause a heart attack.
If the clot is released, it can continue through the bloodstream, blocking blood supply to the brain and causing a stroke.
People who have already had a heart attack are at a higher risk of having another attack.
Ticagrelor, produced by the British company AstraZeneca and sold under the brand name Brilique, reduces the risk by making clots less likely to occur.
The NICE proposal, which was published today, recommends that patients receive 90 mg of ticagrelor for 12 months and then 60 mg together with aspirin twice a day for the next three years.
Professor Carole Longson, director of the NICE Health Technology Assessment Centre, said: “Despite the availability of effective secondary preventive treatment, there are a quarter of patients who have had a heart attack and who will suffer another heart attack or stroke – often with devastating consequences.”
Fear of repetition can have a significant negative impact on a patient’s quality of life.
Ticagrelor in combination with aspirin has been shown to be effective in reducing the risk of further heart attacks and strokes in people who have already had a heart attack.
We are pleased that with Ticagrelor’s preliminary recommendation, we can expand the treatment options available to the many thousands of people who will be able to benefit from it.
Because information on the efficacy and safety of Ticagrelor - in particular the risk of bleeding - beyond three years is limited, treatment beyond this time is not recommended in the proposal.
