Compared to the French, you are not negative, says a Muslim woman living in Prague.
You're from France.
Where did you live before you moved to Prague?
My parents are originally from Algeria.
I was born in the south of France, not far from the Spanish border.
I've moved quite a bit.
I lived in Toulouse, Lyon and Marseille.
In France, I studied journalism, thanks to which I got to work in a magazine.
Why did you decide to move out of the country?
I was beginning to feel like I was suffocating in France.
I just didn't want to live there anymore.
Mainly because of the atmosphere.
I thought every Frenchman was awfully negative.
People in France are generally negative, but things have gotten worse recently.
It's interesting that you're talking about negativity.
This is how some people view the Czech character.
Trust me, you're not negative compared to the French.
Some people may not feel this way when they come to France, because as tourists they do not perceive it so much.
But it was too much for me.
The big issue is money.
People feel that they have little money, while the minimum wage in France is fifteen hundred euros, which, in my opinion, is enough.
Now there is a problem with the behavior of people towards Muslims.
That's completely incomprehensible to me.
For example, in the street where I lived, my non-Muslim neighbor began to look at me through his fingers just because I was a Muslim.
It's like I'm some kind of evil.
I did not feel well in France.
My family stayed there.
So you decided to go to another country.
Why did you choose the Czech Republic?
I was looking for work basically anywhere else and I came across a vacancy at Air France here in Prague.
I must admit that I did not know Prague at all from the beginning.
I knew something about the Czech Republic, my father even told me about what was happening in Czechoslovakia, but I did not know what to expect from Prague at all.
I've been here for three years now, and I can't imagine not living here.
Was it a big difference when you moved from France to Prague?
Mainly because of a different atmosphere.
Maybe it’s because I don’t speak Czech, so I can’t catch any negative reactions or swear words, but I feel like there are more free people here.
That I could do anything, dress any way I wanted, and no one would judge me.
In France, someone is always looking at you unpleasantly, for example, when you have special clothes and the like.
In Prague, I started to feel really free.
I don't think roasters care about that sort of thing.
Where do you work now?
After working at Air France, I worked for a travel website for a while.
Then a friend of mine and I started a website where people offer and look for shared housing.
So far, we only operate in Prague, but we would like to extend it to the whole of Central Europe.
Do you have any Czech friends in Prague?
I have two very close friends who are half Czech, and two Czech friends.
I must say that another peculiarity of the Czechs is that at first they keep more distance.
He won't let anyone get close to him.
That’s quite a difference from where I grew up.
In the south, everyone hugs and kisses each other on the cheek.
It's different here, but I understand it's a cultural thing, so I'm trying to adapt.
You mentioned that you don't speak Czech.
Is the language barrier a problem for you?
On the contrary, I have it quite simple in Prague, because everyone here speaks English.
Even in the evenings or in food.
I would like to learn Czech, but I don’t have that much time.
And by the fact that everyone can communicate in English at least a little, I do not have such a need to learn the language quickly.
And every time I have a problem, there's someone to help me.
Have you had any negative reactions?
Is it because you are a Muslim?
Not really.
Perhaps it is also because I work in an international environment that is more tolerant.
One experience comes to mind.
My manager, the Czech Republic, once told me about the French football team and said something in the sense: They are not French, they are Africans.
That touched me quite a bit.
But that someone would have a problem with me being a Muslim has never happened to me before.
And this despite the fact that a colleague once warned me about some anti-Muslim demonstrations.
He told me not to go downtown, that I'd be scolded.
Anti-Muslim demonstrations are partly linked to terrorist attacks.
How does the current situation affect you?
Are you afraid that something similar to Paris, Nice or Brussels could happen in Prague?
I feel safe in Prague.
But the problem is that nowadays, anything can happen anywhere.
Until recently, I could not imagine that such a thing would happen in France.
This is not just about Muslims.
Moreover, Islam does not recognize violence at all.
For me, the people who kill are not Muslims.
The Qur’an says that man has no right to kill because he is not God.
How do you feel when terrorists protect themselves with your faith?
It's very hard.
I feel shame and guilt, even if I shouldn't feel that way at all.
I try not to follow the reports of violence, but every time I read something, I feel like apologizing for something that's not really my fault.
I'm a completely different person, so why should I apologize for being a terrorist?
We met in the square of Ji<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xAD>ho z Pod<0xC4><0x9B>brad.
On Wednesday, Czech Muslims and Christians demonstrated against the violence.
Did you register it?
I didn't know that.
But I understand that these people feel the need to prove that they disagree with violence.
I don't think they have to do anything like that.
Why should they feel guilty for something they didn't do?
Do you meet other Muslims in Prague?
My co-workers are, for example, from Egypt and other Muslim countries.
They’re a little more religious than I am, so sometimes we have pretty wild discussions about Islam because we all see it a little differently.
I come from France, so I went through a different education, for example, they learned Islam at school.
We have different approaches, but we respect each other.
People sometimes associate Islam with the subordination of women.
How do you feel about it?
I do not feel subordinate in any way.
On the contrary.
I'm a woman, I have strength.
It also has to do with the fact that you are not wearing any headgear.
Hijab, for example?
And it's mostly about the way I was raised.
My mother, for example, is a devout Muslim.
He prays five times a day, but he just doesn't wear a headscarf.
She always taught me that faith is a purely personal thing.
It all depends on how you interpret it.
When a person reads the Qur’an, he should make up his own mind about these things.
So when I read in the Qur’an a passage that says that God told the Prophet to hide his wives from the eyes of others, I said to myself: I am not the Prophet’s wife, so why should I hide?
On the other hand, I respect that, and when I come to Iran or Saudi Arabia, for example, where scarves are required, I take it.
Are you planning to stay in Prague?
So far, yes.
I've never felt so good anywhere else.
I’ve been thinking about Poland for a while, but I’m great in Prague.
I can even imagine raising my own children here.
Prague is an ideal city for this.
