The parliamentary committee said in a report released on Thursday that officers from the U.S. Central Command had altered intelligence reports to paint a more optimistic picture of the war against Islamic State in Iraq and Syria than events from the country provided.
According to a preliminary report by a working group compiled by the Republican chairman of the Armed Services Committee, the Intelligence Committee, and the Subcommittee on Defense, there has been “extensive dissatisfaction” among Central Intelligence analysts that their superiors have altered their assessment of America’s efforts to defeat the Islamic State.
The Central Command, known as CentCom, is the military headquarters in Tampa, Florida, overseeing U.S. military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
The report’s press release states: “The intelligence outputs endorsed by Centcom’s superior officers typically offered a more positive picture of U.S. counterterrorism efforts than has been confirmed by facts on the ground, and were consistently more positive than analyses obtained from other parts of the intelligence community.”
“What happened at Centcom is unacceptable — our fighters are damaged when superior policymakers are presented with a flawed analysis,” said Ken Calvert, a California congressman and Republican.
The failure of Centcom's leadership reaches to the top of the organization.
The 10-page report details the central staff’s persistent problems in describing and analyzing U.S. efforts to train Iraqi forces in 2014 and 2015.
While there is no conclusive evidence that senior Obama administration officials ordered the reports to be amended, the report said analysts felt they had been pressured by Centcom leaders to present a more optimistic view of the dangers posed by the Islamic State, or IS.
“In the first half of 2015, many of the Central Staff’s press releases, statements and congressional testimony were substantially more positive than what actually happened,” the report said.
For example, a Centcom official publicly stated that a major military attack to take Mosul could begin as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul, Iraq’s second-largest city, remains under Islamic State control.
“This is clear after months of investigation,” said Rep. Mike Pompeo, a Kansas Republican.
From mid-2014 to mid-2015, top U.S. Central Command intelligence officials manipulated the staff’s intelligence outputs to downplay the dangers of ISIS in Iraq.
The Republicans formed a task force after learning of analysts’ concerns that intelligence information related to the Islamic State group was being manipulated.
The report, released on Thursday, must be followed by further investigation.
In the intelligence services of Centcom, another investigation led by the Inspector General of the Ministry of Defense is underway.
On Thursday, Democratic members of the Intelligence Committee released their own findings, which corresponded to some of the findings of the Republican task force.
“Between 2014 and 2015, Centcom created a very narrow process for compiling assessments of information on ISIS and Iraqi security forces,” said Adam B. Schiff, chairman of the committee and a Democratic representative.
According to Adam Schiff, this process "led to a distortion of intelligence outputs," damaged morale among analysts, and "did not sufficiently take into account dissenting views."
However, Schiff and the Democrats say they have found no evidence that the White House was trying to pressure Centcom analysts to adjust their conclusions based on "a template or a political situation."
Preliminary results of the parliamentary investigation were published in the Daily Beast on Tuesday.
Last August, the New York Times reported on the ongoing investigation by the Pentagon’s inspector general, which was launched following complaints from Centcom analysts.
Lt. Commander Patrick Evans, a Pentagon spokesman, said in a statement that the Department of Defense would not comment on the parliamentary report as the Inspector General’s investigation is still ongoing.
But he noted that “experts sometimes disagree on the interpretation of complex data, and that the intelligence community and the Department of Defense welcome a healthy dialogue on these critical national security issues.”
The investigation has implications beyond the question of whether the U.S.-led bombing campaign in Iraq and Syria is successful (a statement now being made by a growing number of defense officials).
However, last year’s accusations raised questions about the extent to which President Obama can rely on the Central Staff to honestly assess military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya and other crisis locations.
Criticism of news coverage of the Islamic State has reflected conflicts for more than a decade, when Centcom intelligence analyst Gregory Hooker wrote a research paper stating that the George W. Bush administration - despite the objections of many analysts - defended a small unit in Iraq and devoted little time to thinking about it in 2003.
Hooker also played a key role in the resistance against the intelligence services of the Islamic State.
Last year, authorities reported that Hooker’s team concluded that despite public statements to the contrary, the air strikes conducted against Islamic State refineries did not significantly weaken the terrorist group’s financial resources, as the group built temporary refineries and sold oil on the black market.
The Times reported in September that the findings had not been passed on outside the headquarters.
The commander of Centcom, Gen. Lloyd J. Austin III, was then criticized last year after many lawmakers found the Senate’s testimony too positive an assessment of the war.
General Austin resigned in April and was replaced at Centcom by General Joseph L. Votel.
