"Protest generation" in Ethiopia, a longtime U.S. ally
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Protesters demanding political change in Ethiopia have met with violent opposition from the government.
Witnesses say many protesters were shot dead during clashes with police.
Is there a threat of war in Ethiopia?
In the past decade, it has been one of the most stable nations in Africa, a solid Western alliance with a rapidly growing economy.
In recent months, however, the country has been gripped by anti-government unrest, which has spread to more and more areas.
In the past week alone, thousands of people have taken to the streets demanding major political changes.
Human rights groups say the government's response has been merciless.
Witnesses say police shot and killed scores of unarmed protesters.
Rounding video footage of the protests, likely from the end of last year or early this year, shows security forces beating young people with sticks after they were forced to stand against a wall on their hands.
The UN High Commissioner for Human Rights is now calling for a thorough investigation.
“It’s always been difficult to hold this country together and it’s going to be even harder to take a step forward,” Rashid Abdi, Horn of Africa project manager for the International Crisis Group, said in a statement.
Ethiopia is the second most populous nation in Africa after Nigeria, and its stability is supported by the West.
U.S. military and intelligence agencies are working closely with the Ethiopians to eliminate the threat of a terrorist attack in the region, particularly in Somalia, and few African countries, if any, are receiving such aid from the West.
The economy of Ethiopia has been developing at an impressive pace.
Its infrastructure has improved dramatically, with a new commuter train running in the capital, Addis Ababa.
And the streets of the city are typically quiet, safe and clean.
But Ethiopia can hardly be described as a model of democracy - human rights organizations are constantly talking about government repression - opposition in the country has been suppressed, dissidents effectively silenced.
Many were banished, imprisoned, killed, or driven far into the desert.
However, this may change.
“When you strangle people and they have no choice but to protest, there will be a breakthrough,” said Seyoum Teshome, who teaches at the University of Central Ethiopia.
They are protesting all the youth.
A whole generation is protesting.
Complaints range from land disputes to absolute control of power by the ruling coalition.
After last year’s election, which was widely criticized, the ruling party and its allies won the last seat held by the opposition and now controls 100 percent of parliament.
At the same time, pressure is mounting on the border with Eritrea, a conflict along this imprecisely marked, disputed border that has claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatist groups that have been more or less suppressed over the past years, such as the Oromsk Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, may try to exploit the confusion and re-arm themselves.
There are several factors that explain why now, after years of smoldering beneath the surface, these bitter feelings have flared up again.
The first one is seemingly harmless: smart phones.
Many Ethiopians can communicate through social networks only in the last few years, when cheaper smartphones have become commonly available and the provision of Internet services has improved.
And even if the government bans access to Facebook or Twitter, as is usually the case, especially during protests, many people can still communicate through Internet proxies that hide the location of these people.
Several young Ethiopians spoke about how they had gathered for the protests.
There is also greater solidarity between the Oroms and Amhars, the two largest ethnic groups in Ethiopia.
The Oroms and Amhars are not natural allies.
For centuries, the Amhars, mostly from the Christian highlands of Ethiopia, excelled in politics and commerce and used the Oroms, many of whom are Muslims and live in the lowlands.
But that's also changing.
"We are on our way to unified leadership," said Mulatu Gemechu, leader of the Oroms.
The largest protests took place in the areas inhabited by Amhara and Oroma.
Many Amhars and Oromians believe that Ethiopia is wrongly dominated by members of the Tigrayan ethnic group, which makes up about 6 percent of the population and controls the military, intelligence, trade and politics.
The third reason for the unrest is the death of Meles Zenawi.
Zenawi, a former rebel leader, served as Ethiopian prime minister for 17 years until his death in 2012, when he succumbed to an unspecified illness.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could see around the corner.
Analysts say he was particularly skilled at spotting initial signs of discontent and using envoys to work through opponents and win him over.
"The current regime lacks basic knowledge," said Abdi, a conflict analyst.
Ethiopia's new prime minister, Hailemariam Desalegin, was pulled out of relative obscurity with the aim of replacing Zenawi.
Unlike Zenawi, who came from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam comes from the south.
Analysts say he has no confidence in the Tigray-controlled security services.
Many fear that the result will be more bloodshed.
Ethiopia last experienced such unrest in 2005 after thousands of people protested against what analysts described as elections that the government picked up and then stole.
This was followed by a severe crackdown, during which many protesters were killed - albeit less than in recent months - and this period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts praised Ethiopia’s leaders for visionary infrastructure planning, such as a new commuter train and measurable progress in the fight against poverty.
However, it is quite clear that the gradual escalation of disputes within the Ethiopian government has not stopped.
And there is a dangerous ethnic formation.
Last month, protesters in the Amharic city of Gondar attacked business firms owned by Tigrayans, and resentment against Tigrayans on social media has become more common.
Analysts say the protests put the U.S. and other Western allies in an awkward position.
The U.S. government is using Ethiopia as a base for drone flights over neighboring Somalia, although it recently said the base had been closed.
While the West clearly wants to support democracy, it also does not want its ally to disintegrate in an already volatile region.
"That," said Abdi, "is a very sharp edge of the blade."
