NASA climate model: Venus was once habitable
According to NASA’s new climate model, Venus was once habitable.
Scientists at NASA’s Goddard Institute for Space Studies have developed a model for studying Venus using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climate scientists.
The model was designed to determine whether conditions similar to those on Earth once existed on Venus, whose surface is hot, waterless, and saturated with CO2.
Scientists have previously suggested that Venus' low rotational speed can be explained by its dense atmosphere.
But according to the latest simulations, Venus may have once boasted a thin, Earth-like atmosphere while spinning slowly.
The model also dealt with the earlier topography of Venus.
There may have been drier areas on the planet than on Earth, but there was once enough water and geographical diversity to rule life and provide protection against rapid evaporation.
Venus has also previously used the sun, which was 30 percent more subdued.
“In a simulation of the GISS model, Venus exposes its day side to the sun almost two months at a time during a slow rotation,” explained GISS scientist Anthony Del Genio in a new report.
This heats the surface and creates rain, which creates a thick layer of clouds that act as an umbrella and protect the surface from excessive solar heat.
The result is a climate with average temperatures that are in fact slightly lower than those currently on Earth.
The model compiled a story of Venus similar to evolution, which was previously hypothetically compiled by planetary scientists.
Although Venus was probably habitable in the past -- over several billion years -- it was exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet radiation.
Its oceans evaporated and water vapor was burned by ultraviolet light.
Hydrogen escaped, leaving only a dense atmosphere of carbon dioxide with the deadly effect of greenhouse gas -- that's Venus as we know it today.
The researchers published their results from the new Venus climate model in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
