Oil rig workers in the North Sea resume talks, end strike
The leaders of the two sides said strikes over wages for oil rig workers in the North Sea have been suspended, while all parties to the dispute have come together for a new round of negotiations.
Strikes against the oilfield services company Wood Group have occasionally taken place on platforms in the North Sea operated by Royal Dutch Shell.
“Wood Group and the Unite and RMT trade unions can confirm that they have agreed to resume the process to resolve current disagreements,” the statement said.
Starting next week, we will have a series of all-day meetings over the next few weeks, where we will try to look at problems from new angles.
According to trade unions, their recent action, which they say was the first in more than 25 years, is up to 30 percent to protest wage cuts.
Wood Group has cut rates this year and paid out about 9 percent less to its North Sea suppliers due to negative market pressure.
The reduction in company rates comes after a 10% reduction for coastal companies in 2014.
The company argues that further cuts would give the company room to cope with the market downturn.
On the other hand, Shell has cut thousands of people from its payroll and announced plans to exit oil and gas operations in up to 10 countries to modernise its processes – immediately after a mega merger with the British energy company BG Group.
Energy companies are under pressure due to low oil prices, the economic situation associated with the June decision of Britain to leave the European Union.
Scottish MP Dave Anderson met with union leaders earlier this week to discuss one of the biggest labour disagreements of a generation that led to a strike in the North Sea.
The North Sea, he said, is vital to the region's economy.
“In the North Sea and across the country, we need an economy that works for everyone, not just some,” he said.
For comparison, nearly $1.4 billion is expected to be invested in new projects in the North Sea in 2016, while the average over the past five years has been around $7 billion.
Kepler measures the rotational speed of stars in the Pleiades
The latest mission of the Kepler space telescope to help astronomers is to obtain an almost complete list of the rotational speeds of stars from the Pleiades star cluster.
The new data helps astronomers understand why stars in the cluster rotate at different speeds, and how the rotation time is related to the formation of the planet.
“We hope that by comparing our results with other clusters, we will learn more about the relationship between stellar mass, its age, and even the history of its solar system,” said Luisa Rebull, a researcher at Caltech’s Infrared Processing and Analysis Center in Pasadena.
The Pleiades Cluster is located 445 light-years from Earth.
Many stars in the cluster are now reaching adulthood and have formed over 125 million years ago.
Now it rotates the fastest.
At the moments of maximum rotational speeds, these adolescence stars release huge amounts of stellar wind.
Because these winds move along the magnetic fields of stars, they have a slowing effect on them.
As the star ages, its rotational speed slows down.
Kepler measures the rotational speed of each star by measuring the time between the detection of recognisable points on stars -- like sunspots.
According to the latest data on rotational velocities, larger stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Rebull compares the stars to dancers, the larger ones make pirouettes slower than the smaller ones.
"In the Pleiades ballet, we see that the slower-rotating stars are more massive, while the ones that spin the fastest are usually very light stars," Rebull said.
Because the Pleiades cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory for comparing star quality and rotational speeds.
"The Pleiades provide us with an anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation in both directions, in younger and older stars," Rebull said.
There’s still a lot we want to know about how, when and why stars slow down their rotational speed, so to speak, “hanging their dance shoes on a nail.”
Rebull and her colleagues detailed the latest analysis of Pleiades rotational speeds in three studies that will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
Is a Qualifying Agreement Necessary?
If I did not apply, then the qualification agreement would not be concluded and after a few months I could move to another hospital?
Is it even possible to work after graduation without applying to specialized education?
My point is that in the field in which I would like to work, there is now a vacancy only in a slightly more distant hospital, but in about half a year, a place in another, where I would like to work, could be freed up.
I do not know how to deal with the situation for about six months, the question continues.
Answered by Mgr. Lenka Vlková.
No legislation provides for the obligation to conclude a qualification agreement with the employer - hospital.
A qualification agreement is a legal institution regulated by the Labour Code and may be concluded between the employee and the employer in order to ensure the return of the costs incurred in increasing or deepening the qualification of the employee.
In the area of health, there is a long-standing pressure not to conclude these agreements with a view to ensuring the labour mobility of health workers, and not all hospitals currently require this agreement.
According to Act No. 95/2004 Coll., on conditions for obtaining and recognition of professional competence and specialized competence for the medical profession of a doctor, dentist and pharmacist, it is expressly true that participation in specialized education is considered to be a deepening of qualifications (not an increase in it).
This means that a qualification agreement can only be concluded under the Labour Code if the costs are at least CZK 75,000.
No legal regulation even provides for the obligation to apply for specialized education.
The law only specifies the conditions for applying for inclusion in the field of specialized education.
However, according to the law, a doctor is entitled to practice the profession of a doctor already due to the completion of the necessary university studies, albeit under the conditions established by law (under the professional supervision of a doctor with specialized competence in the relevant field).
The law foresees a situation in which professional experience completed in another field of specialization may be included in the specialist training of a doctor, if its content and scope correspond to the relevant educational program.
Theoretically, it would be possible to count the time worked elsewhere, which would correspond to the situation of the interviewer.
However, given that I do not know the circumstances of this case, it is advisable to consult the relevant department of the Ministry of Health (the Department of Science and Medical Professions), since the Ministry of Health by law provides advisory and consulting services related to the inclusion in special education and its course.
The advisory service is also provided free of charge by the Czech Medical Chamber, of which every doctor must be a member.
Doctors in Halab, Syria, are calling for U.S. intervention.
The United States made no effort to end the siege (insurgent areas of the city by government troops) and did not use its influence to enforce the protection of civilians, the White House said in a letter.
“We do not need tears, compassion, or even prayer; however, we desperately need to create a no-fly zone over eastern Halab to stop the attacks, and we need international action to ensure that Halab is not besieged again,” the doctors said.
Russian forces, which support an army loyal to President Bashar al-Assad, have announced they will stop strikes in the Halab area every day for three hours from today to allow safe passage for humanitarian convoys.
From 9 a.m. to 12 p.m., all military activities, air strikes and artillery fire are to be stopped.
U.N. humanitarian chief Stephen O’Brien welcomed the move, but said a two-day truce was needed.
In the letter, 15 of the 35 doctors working in the eastern part of Halab, which is controlled by the rebels, addressed Obama, according to AFP.
He writes that during the five-year war they witnessed the violent, cruel death of countless patients, friends and colleagues.
The world is watching and noting how complex Syria is, but doing little to protect us.
Recent offers to evacuate residents from the Syrian regime and Russia sound like only slightly veiled threats, pediatricians, surgeons and other doctors said.
Doctors said there have been 42 attacks on medical facilities in Syria in the past month, 15 of them on hospitals where they work.
The saddest part is that we have to decide who lives and who dies.
Young children come to the emergency room with such serious injuries that we have to choose among them those who are most likely to survive.
And sometimes we do not even have the necessary material to help them, doctors describe.
Two weeks ago, four newborns suffocated when an explosion cut off oxygen supplies to their incubators.
They were gasping for breath, and then their lives were over — before he could really begin, they recalled.
An army loyal to President Bashar al-Assad, backed by Russian forces, has encircled rebel-held eastern Halab in recent weeks, leaving more than 200,000 people without food supplies inside.
The rebels, who are under constant strikes by the Russian and Syrian air forces, managed to break through the encirclement after three weeks on Saturday and launch a counteroffensive.
Both sides were then reinforced in the city and its surroundings.
